---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Secure Password Management & MFA Best Practices | Sheepdog" description="Implement password managers and multi-factor authentication. Learn best practices for credential management and access control." showMatrix={true}>
  <section>
    <h1>Secure Password Management & MFA Best Practices</h1>
    <p class="lead">Passwords alone don't work. Users reuse weak passwords across sites, and breaches expose millions of credentials. Modern security requires password managers and multi-factor authentication as baseline controls.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The Password Problem</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Users choose weak passwords (123456, password, qwerty)</li>
      <li>Users reuse the same password across multiple sites</li>
      <li>Password breaches expose millions of credentials</li>
      <li>Attackers use breached passwords to compromise other accounts</li>
      <li>Password resets are inconvenient so users avoid them</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Password Manager Benefits</h2>
    
    <h3>For Individuals</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Generate and store strong, unique passwords</li>
      <li>No need to remember passwords</li>
      <li>Auto-fill passwords on websites</li>
      <li>Identify weak or reused passwords</li>
      <li>Check for credentials in breaches</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>For Organizations</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Enterprise password manager for employees</li>
      <li>Shared credentials without exposing passwords</li>
      <li>Audit access to shared credentials</li>
      <li>Enforce password policies</li>
      <li>Credential rotation and expiration</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Top Password Managers</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>1Password:</strong> Enterprise-friendly, strong security</li>
      <li><strong>Bitwarden:</strong> Open source, affordable</li>
      <li><strong>LastPass:</strong> Popular, widely integrated</li>
      <li><strong>Dashlane:</strong> User-friendly, strong focus on security</li>
      <li><strong>KeePass:</strong> Open source, self-hosted option</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)</h2>
    
    <h3>Why MFA is Essential</h3>
    <p>Even if passwords are compromised:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Attackers can't login without the second factor</li>
      <li>Protects against credential reuse attacks</li>
      <li>Protects against phishing attacks</li>
      <li>Required for compliance (HIPAA, PCI, SOC 2)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>MFA Methods by Effectiveness</h3>
    
    <h4>Hardware Security Keys (Most Secure)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Physical key (USB or NFC)</li>
      <li>Resistant to phishing</li>
      <li>High cost and user friction</li>
      <li>Examples: YubiKey, Google Titan</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Authenticator Apps (Recommended)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Time-based one-time passwords (TOTP)</li>
      <li>Generated by app on phone</li>
      <li>Works offline</li>
      <li>Vulnerable to SIM swap if phone stolen</li>
      <li>Examples: Google Authenticator, Microsoft Authenticator</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Push Notifications (User-Friendly)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Notification sent to phone</li>
      <li>User approves or denies login</li>
      <li>Better UX than TOTP</li>
      <li>Requires phone with internet</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>SMS/Text Messages (Not Recommended)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Code sent via text</li>
      <li>Vulnerable to SIM swap attacks</li>
      <li>NIST recommends against for sensitive accounts</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Voice Calls (Weakest)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Code read over phone call</li>
      <li>Most vulnerable to social engineering</li>
      <li>Avoid for important accounts</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Implementing Password & MFA Programs</h2>
    
    <h3>For Organizations</h3>
    
    <h4>Phase 1: Assessment</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify all password-protected systems</li>
      <li>Assess current password policies</li>
      <li>Evaluate MFA capabilities</li>
      <li>Identify privileged accounts needing protection</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Phase 2: Password Policies</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Minimum 12 characters (longer is better than complex)</li>
      <li>No reuse of previous passwords</li>
      <li>Password expiration every 90 days for sensitive accounts</li>
      <li>Account lockout after failed attempts</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Phase 3: Password Manager Deployment</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Select enterprise password manager</li>
      <li>Implement for IT and security teams first</li>
      <li>Expand to all users</li>
      <li>Train users on secure usage</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Phase 4: MFA Rollout</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Require MFA for remote access (VPN, email)</li>
      <li>Require MFA for privileged accounts</li>
      <li>Require MFA for all users within 6 months</li>
      <li>Support multiple MFA methods</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Phase 5: Verification & Maintenance</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Verify compliance (who has MFA enabled?)</li>
      <li>Monitor for MFA bypass attempts</li>
      <li>Maintain backup MFA methods</li>
      <li>Regular audits of access</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Common MFA Implementation Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Only requiring MFA for employees, not contractors/vendors</li>
      <li>Allowing users to choose weak MFA methods (SMS)</li>
      <li>No backup MFA method for lost devices</li>
      <li>Not enforcing MFA for remote access</li>
      <li>Allowing MFA bypass for "convenience"</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Passwordless Authentication</h2>
    <p>Future of authentication (no passwords at all):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Windows Hello (biometric authentication)</li>
      <li>FIDO2 security keys</li>
      <li>Passwordless sign-in (email/phone verification)</li>
      <li>Biometric authentication (fingerprint, face recognition)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Credential Hygiene</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Never share passwords (use password manager for shared access)</li>
      <li>Never write down passwords</li>
      <li>Never use same password twice</li>
      <li>Change password immediately if compromised</li>
      <li>Use different password for work vs personal accounts</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="cta">
    <h2>Implement Password & MFA Programs</h2>
    <p>Sheepdog Cyber Defense helps organizations deploy password managers and MFA solutions aligned with security best practices.</p>
    <a href="/contact" class="btn">Build Your MFA Program</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

